  <title>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Mafura: Market and supply development to bring scale benefits</narrative>
  </title>
  <description>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Thousands of small farmers in Mozambique live on less than a dollar a day, work on land with low levels of production and are vulnerable to drought and climate change. Seeds from the wild-growing mafura tree can be freely accessed by women and sold to local processors of mafura oil. This project will support the formation of harvester groups and link them to local oil processors to revive an industry that declined due to competition from cheap palm oil.  Mafura is similar to palm oil and is exciting to European buyers who are looking for an ethical alternative due to the negative social and environmental impacts of palm plantation production. The oil will first be produced for the local market whilst building the capacity of local oil processors to prepare for export. Harvesters will be trained to increase the harvest of seed, quality and storage methods to meet market demands. Research will determine the quantity of mafura fruit and technical information needed to secure the interest of international buyers in an alternative to palm oil for use in products like cosmetics. The increase in demand will bring more harvesters into gathering seeds and generate income for thousands of poor women.</narrative>
  </description>
